\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs24\keepn\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 {\uldb \{bml CONTROL.SHG\}}{\v contents>Main}Step-by-Step Tutorial - Create Your First ePhoto Book}\par
\pard\plain{}
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 \line This tutorial assumes you understand the basics of using your Windows computer. This includes making folders, creating files and moving files around. If you are unclear on how to do these things, the Windows help file has all that information. You could also have one of your computer savvy friends sit with you for about an hour and show you how to do all that. It might also be a good idea to have them sit through this tutorial with you if you are not all that computer knowledgeable.\line }\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 Sample Projects}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 "Share the Memories" comes with one sample project which includes a few pictures you can use to experiment using the program options. For this tutorial, we are going to set up our own project folders and use the files in the  "Sample ePhoto book" project. At any time you can open this project into "Share the Memories" and see how it was set up, but for now we are just going to use these files for the tutorial.\line }\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 Set Up Your Project Folders}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 First let's start by making a folder on your C:/ drive. This is the folder that will have all your files in them. Each project folder will hold all the bitmaps, text  and associated project files.\line }\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 Let's Make a Project}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 1.  For this example, make a folder (example: C:\\My ePhoto Book); this is your project folder so feel free to substitute the folder name for a name that better suites your needs.\line \line 2.  "Share the Memories" comes with sample bitmap files to give  you something to experiment with. Copy these files to your project folder. You can find these files in the "Share the Memories" application folder, C:\\Program Files\\ShareTheMemories\\Sample ePhoto book. \line      These files are:\line      Sample Page01.jpg\line      Sample Page02.jpg\line      Sample Page03.jpg\line      Sample Page04.jpg\line      Sample Startup.jpg\line      Sample Tile Background.gif\line \line 3.  Run the  "Share the Memories" program if it's not already running.\line \line 4.  Let's start by creating a new project. Use your mouse to click on the "File" menu and then select the "New Project" menu option.\line \line 5.  Use the "Save In:" combo box to make your way over to your project folder (example: C:\\My ePhoto Book) or whatever you named it.\line \line 6.  In the "File Name:" edit field, type in a project name. Name it anything you want or type in "My ePhoto Book". This will make your project file which holds all your ePhoto book settings. Don't get this confused with your EXE file which is your executable for sending to other people.\line \line 7.  The "Project Preferences" window should now pop up. Feel free to change any of the information. The "Project Preferences" window is covered in greater depth under the "Project Preferences" section of this help file. This is where you can type what the name of your EXE file is. Once you start sending your ePhoto Books to your family and friends, be sure to change the name of this file so that the newest ePhoto book you send doesn't overwrite any previous ePhoto books of yours they may already have.\line \line 8.  Now let's add some pages. Click on the "Project" menu and then click on the "Add Page(s)" menu option. "Share the Memories" considers each bitmap or text file a page.\line \line 9. Have file "Sample Page01.jpg" to "Sample Page04.jpg" selected. "Share the Memories" adds files in alphabetical order.\line \line 10. Click on the "Open" button to load all these images. All the image files you select will be loaded in alphabetical order. Depending on  the size, format and number of files selected, the loading process may take a second or two because each file that is loaded is being checked.\line \line 11. When the loading process is complete, you'll see the very last page in this project. Click on the arrow buttons to go from page to page.\line \line 12. Under the "Project" menu you will find two menu options you can experiment with, "Move Current Page" and "Delete Current Page." Feel free to move any of the pages around and delete any of the pages if you want.\line \line 13. We are now ready to build the EXE program.  Click on the "File" menu and then click on the "Save" menu option. You could also click on the "Project" menu and then click on the "Run Project" menu option to run your ePhoto book.\line \line 14. The file that has been generated is yours to distribute to your friends and family. Note: The program generated by the shareware version of "Share the Memories" will only run on your computer. Only licensed users of "Share the Memories" can distribute the generated executable.\line \line 15. That's it in a nutshell. Read the "Preferences" section of this help file for more information on the different program preference options.\line \line You have created your first ePhoto book (unless this is a refresher course). You will also notice that it is a program file. This file requires nothing extra to run and anyone you email it to will be able to enjoy your photos.\line }\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 Extra Credit Work\line }\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 If you're one of those overachievers, and I know you are, you can give your ePhoto book that extra flair by adding a startup screen and a background tile bitmap. If you have closed out your project, you'll need to load you project file before you can do the following.\line \line 1.    Let's start by adding the startup screen by clicking on the "File" menu and then selecting the "Preferences..." menu option.\line \line 2.    In the "Build Preferences:" group, click on the "Select bitmap for startup screen" check box.\line \line 3.    Select the "Sample startup.jpg" file and click on the "Open" button to use this bitmap file as your startup screen. A startup screen gives your program a more polished look.\line \line 4.    You'll now notice the "Select bitmap for startup screen" check box is selected. Clicking on this check box again unselects the bitmap file that was chosen for the startup screen.\line \line 5.    Now click on the "Select Background Tile Bitmap" and select the "Sample Tile Background.gif" file. This is the graphic that will tile the background to give your program an even more polished look.\line \line 6.    Click OK in the  "Project Preferences" window to save your changes. Now would be a good time to save your project file, so click on the "File" menu and then select the "Save" menu option.\line \line 7.    We are now ready to view these new changes so click on the "Project" menu and then click on the "Run Project" menu option to run your ePhoto book. You'll see the startup screen when your ePhoto book loads and the new tiled background that we just added.\line \line Just think how much your family and friends will enjoy seeing your photos.}\par
