\pard\plain{}
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 \line What is "Share the Memories"}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 "Share the Memories" is a software package that will give you the ability to make electronic photo books you can send to anyone. The file you send is all they will need to view your pictures. You can also include sound files and captions.\line \line * This is a full working shareware version except for the fact that the electronic photo books generated while in shareware mode will only run on the computer they were made. You will need to pay the registration fee to be licensed to use the "Share the Memories"-generated electronic photo book files.}\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 \line What is a Stand-Alone Executable File?}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 An executable file is any file with the *.EXE extension. This is a program and it will run when the file is double-clicked on. "Stand-Alone" means the program requires nothing else to run. Many programs need other files with an extension of, *.DLL, *.OCX, and *.VBX to run. Without these files, the programs won't run. "Share the Memories" was designed so that it is as simple as it can be for your friends and family to download and use. Having only one file to download and run is as simple as you can get and your friends and family will appreciate that. Also, because your ePhoto book is a stand-alone executable, no install is needed.}\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 \line My "Share the Memories" executable file size is huge. Is there anything I can do to make it smaller?}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 Part of your ePhoto book file is the program. This part is very small; everything else is the files you added. Did you save your image files as a compressed file format like *.GIF or *.JPG? Windows *.BMP files are not compressed and take up a lot of space quickly. It's quite possible to have image files saved in *.GIF or *.JPG format, but will still remain rather large because the nature of the image does not compress well. Also, even though your images are in a compressed format, they may be bigger than what is really needed and all you're doing is carrying around a lot of extra baggage that's not really necessary. Look at the file size of your images. If you're using *.JPG files, experiment with the amount of compression that provides a small file while still keeping the quality of the image. Some images still look good after they have been crunched down as hard as possible, so experiment with the JPEG compression in your image software.\line \line If you have added sound files, they, too, can be large in size. There are utilities that can save your sound files in compressed formats.\line \line Go to the section "Preparing Your Picture Files" for more information.\line }\par
\pard\plain{\b\cf5\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 How many pictures can I put into my ePhoto book?}\par
\pard\plain{\cf1\f4\fs20\li216\ql\ri216\sa20\sb20 There's no limit. You can add as many as you want. Each image you add increases the size of your ePhoto book so the limit will be determined by the intended use of your ePicture book and if that use has any file size limitations. Obviously, you are making an ePhoto book to email to someone, so you don't want the file size to be too big or it will take too long to download. If you plan on making an ePhoto book to put on a CD, you could have one that will fill the entire space of the CD. That may be too many pictures for one ePhoto book and you may want to break it down into categories, but the possibility is there if you want to.\line }\par
